04827nam a22007215i 9780814762356DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147623567 a10.18574/nyu/9780814762349.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547541  a(OCoLC)913785081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ799.T9bO99 2016 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a306.70835095612231 aOzyegin, Gul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNew Desires, New Selves :bSex, Love, and Piety among Turkish Youth /cGul Ozyegin. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b7 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Virginal Façades -- tPassive Resistance and Class in Lesbian Self-Making: Alev’s Story -- t2. Making a New Man: Recognition, Romance, Sex, and Neoliberal Masculinity -- tVulnerable Masculinity and Self-Transformation: Ali’s Story -- t3. New Pious Female Selves: The Feminist “Vein” Within and the Troubling Gender Divide -- tBecoming a Sade Pious Woman in a Secular Society: Aknur’s Story -- t4. Desire between “Doing” and “Being”: İbne (Faggot) and Gey (Gay) -- tThe Classless Penis -- tConclusion -- tAppendix I: Tables -- tAppendix II: Sampling Procedure -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs Turkey pushes for its place in the global pecking order and embraces neoliberal capitalism, the nation has seen a period of unprecedented shifts in political, religious, and gender and sexual identities for its citizens. In New Desires, New Selves, Gul Ozyegin shows how this social transformation in Turkey is felt most strongly among its young people, eager to surrender to the seduction of sexual modernity, but also longing to remain attached to traditional social relations, identities and histories. Engaging a wide array of upwardly-mobile young adults at a major Turkish university, Ozyegin links the biographies of individuals with the biography of a nation, revealing their creation of conflicted identities in a country which has existed uneasily between West and East, modern and traditional, and secular and Islamic. For these young people, sexuality, gender expression, and intimate relationships in particular serve as key sites for reproducing and challenging patriarchy and paternalism that was hallmark of earlier generations. As Ozyegin evocatively shows, the quest for sexual freedom and an escape from patriarchal constructions of selfless femininity and protective masculinity promise both personal transformations and profound sexual guilt and anxiety. A poignant and original study, New Desires, New Selves presents a snapshot of cultural change on the eve of rapid globalization in the Muslim world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aYouthxReligious lifexTurkeyxTurkey. 0aYouthxReligious lifezTurkey. 0aYouthxSexual behaviorxTurkey. 0aYouthxSexual behaviorzTurkey. 0aYouthxSocial conditionsxTurkey. 0aYouthzTurkeyxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831107289960 cprintz978081476234940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814762349.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762356423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814762356/original  a978-3-11-072899-6  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  